       </p>
      </div>
      <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA05d224n1-ptr" id="PJA05d224n1">1</a>
       <p>On 8 Nov. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington C. Ford and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;, Washington, 19041937; 34 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 9:881).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA05d224n2-ptr" id="PJA05d224n2">2</a>
       <p>A copy of Burgoynes letter to Gates of 14 Nov. is in <span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early 19th century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e. the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 57, f. 31.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#PJA05d224n3-ptr" id="PJA05d224n3">3</a>
       <p>Sir Robert Pigot wrote from Newport, R.I., in the full expectation that Burgoyne would be allowed to embark his army from there (same, f. 79, a copy).</p>
      </div>
